sec.p:
Rule 10b‐18 provides firms with protection from charges of stock price manipulation when repurchasing common stock in the open market. It covers all repurchases of common stock with the exception of those made in conjunction with tender offers or mergers and acquisitions involving recapitalizations. The rule states that an issuer will not be found to have violated Section 9(a)(2) of the Securities Act of 1933 or Rule 10b‐5 under the act, solely by reason of the time or price of bids and purchases, as long as the following five conditions are met:

                     1.

Purchases and bids are effected through one broker or dealer on any given day;


                     2.

No purchase constitutes the opening transaction in the consolidated system;


                     3.

No purchase occurs in the 30 minutes before the end of the period in which the last sale prices are recorded in the consolidated system;


                     4.

No purchase price exceeds the greater of the highest independent published bid and the last independent sale price;


                     5.

Nonblock purchases for a day do not exceed the greater of one round lot and the number of round lots closest to 25% of the security’s trading volume.

Potential discrepancies between 10b‐18 declared intent and execution introduce the possibility that noncompliance is strategic and intended to influence market returns. Detecting a systematic relationship between stock returns and noncomplying repurchases is one approach to addressing the economic significance, if any, of noncompliance. Accordingly, we test for abnormal returns on days when firms execute repurchases in compliance with Rule 10b‐18 and on days when they repurchase outside of the safe harbor. We also test for a differential market impact on 10b‐18 complying versus noncomplying days. Following Schipper and Thompson (1983), we specify the return‐generating process for each firm as

